<br>
Once the pull group is made, it's about balancing healing with aggro.<br>
<br>
The classes that want aggro when played effectively are Warriors, Paladins and Shadowknights.  A warrior usually has higher armor and hit points, plus the defensive discipline; over time, you want aggro on warriors.  A Paladin or Shadowknight has the ability to build aggro faster but are not as efficient on the clerics.<br>
<br>
The highest clerics with the largest mana pools should be partnered with those who will hold the aggro.  Those with aggro will need to be healed the most, and the cleric is the best healer.  Sometimes aggro is kept on one or two main tanks, with possibly two clerics watching the one tank.<br>
<br>
Offensive tanks like Beastlords, Rogues, Rangers and Monks will occasionally gain aggro, but ideally they do not.  With the exception of the pull group, a Druid, Shaman or Paladin can usually serve as main healer for these classes.<br>
<br>
Like offensive tanks, nuker or magic damage dealers like Magicians, Necromancers, Wizards don't get aggro in most situations, if they play their class well.<br>
<br>
Sometimes you want a recovery group.  This could a necromancer or two for twitching, a magician for Mod Rods, a cleric for rez's and a bard for hit point/mana song.  Its optional, but if you'll need to rez and rebuff as part of the raid, especially the debuffers who stand a good chance of dying almost immediately.. <br>
<br>
Play around with it, nothing is perfect, but it comes with time and practice.  Just remember when building groups, its about the success of the raid... as in killing the mobs as quickly as possible with as little mana drain and death along the way... it is not about building several group which each have a shot at experience.<br>
